ingdom"},"cs":{"about 1340–":"okolo 1340–Zesnulá","1340–Male":"1340–Zesnulý","1355–Male":"1355–Zesnulý","1340–Female":"1340–Zesnulá","Abt 1355":"okolo 1355","1455":"1455","1355":"1355","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","about 1340":"okolo 1340","England":"Anglie","England, United Kingdom":"Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"about 1340–":"omkring 1340–Afdød","1340–Male":"1340–Afdød","1355–Male":"1355–Afdød","1340–Female":"1340–Afdød","Abt 1355":"omkring 1355","1455":"1455","1355":"1355","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","about 1340":"omkring 1340","England":"England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1340–":"circa 1340–Overleden","1340–Male":"1340–Overleden","1355–Male":"1355–Overleden","1340–Female":"1340–Overleden","Abt 1355":"circa 1355","1455":"1455","1355":"1355","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","about 1340":"circa 1340","England":"England","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1340–":"about 1340–Deceased","1340–Male":"1340–Deceased","1355–Male":"1355–Deceased","1340–Female":"1340–Deceased","Abt 1355":"about 1355","1455":"1455","1355":"1355","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","about 1340":"about 1340","England":"England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hannah","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the mother of the prophet Samuel (1 Samuel 1:2), Hebrew <i>Hanna</i>. It is derived from a Hebrew word meaning ‘He (i.e. God) has favoured me (i.e. with a child)’.  See also  Anne .  This form of the name was taken up as a given name by the Puritans in the 16th and 17th centuries and remained popular until the late 19th century. Thereafter it fell somewhat from favour but has enjoyed a massive revival since the 1990s."],"variants":[{"name":"Hanna","meanings":["Either the biblical name (  see  <b>Hannah</b>   ) or a short form of   Johanna ."]},{"name":"Hana","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":42,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705197,"age":115,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Hannah was born about 1340, in England. She had at least 1 son with Edward Bunne."},"et":{"about 1340–":"umbes 1340–Surnud","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","1355–Male":"1355–Surnud","1340–Female":"1340–Surnud","Abt 1355":"umbes 1355","1455":"1455","1355":"1355","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","about 1340":"umbes 1340","England":"England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1340–":"noin 1340–Kuollut","1340–Male":"1340–Kuollut","1355–Male":"1355–Kuollut","1340–Female":"1340–Kuollut","Abt 1355":"noin 1355","1455":"1455","1355":"1355","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","about 1340":"noin 1340","England":"England","England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1340–":"environ 1340–Décédée","1340–Male":"1340–Décédé","1355–Male":"1355–Décédé","1340–Female":"1340–Décédée","Abt 1355":"environ 1355","1455":"1455","1355":"1355","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","about 1340":"environ 1340","England":"Angleterre","England, United Kingdom":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Hannah est née environ 1340, à Angleterre. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Edward Bunne."},"de":{"about 1340–":"um 1340–Verstorben","1340–Male":"1340–Verstorben","1355–Male":"1355–Verstorben","1340–Female":"1340–Verstorben","Abt 1355":"um 1355","1455":"1455","1355":"1355","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","about 1340":"um 1340","England":"England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"Hannah wurde um 1340 in England geboren. Sie hatte mit Edward Bunne mindestens 1 Sohn."},"ht":{"about 1340–":"about 1340–Desede","1340–Male":"1340–Desede","1355–Male":"1355–Desede","1340–Fem